Texinfo tree reader
===================

The following information is about code related to the Reader and TreeElement
interface that is abandonned.  It may refer to code removed from version
control.  It is kept in case this code would be developped again.


The code in Texinfo/Reader*.pm, Texinfo/TreeElement*.pm and
Texinfo/Convert/TreeElementConverter*.pm and associated XS interfaces
allow to go through the Texinfo tree, possibly without building the tree to
perl.  There are two examples of Docbook converters, one using the
TreeElement+Reader interface, the other using the Reader only in
Texinfo/Example.

This code relies on calling methods in Perl, which is slow (about 10 time
slower to call a function compared to accessing a hash key), requires
carefully registering handles in Perl to find the C elements data in XS
and doing many XS interfaces and different code in Perl.

Therefore, currently this code is not used in texi2any, and not developped
further.  The SWIG interface in util/swig, even if less flexible and less
elegantly integrated in Perl also allows to wrap the C code, is much easier
to develop and maintain, and multi language.


There could be a TreeElement interface for element destruction that
would nullify the corresponding handle in document->element_handles, and
remove the associated information in Perl element hash.

There could be a possibility to relinquish the handles in
document->element_handles and remove the associated information in Perl element
hash, even though the elements are not destroyed.  This could even be
automatic, for example when reaching a root command @node or sectioning command
through the Reader.

It could also be possible to remove and destroy elements that are stored
in document->additional_elements, that were added by new_tree_element() but
it should be made sure that they will not be accessed again, which could
be difficult to make sure of.

All the Document interfaces lead to rebuilding the tree, and wiping out
the handles for access through the TreeElement interface.  The TreeElement
interface may still be used in some cases because the XS code also process
the rebuilt tree, as would Perl do.  It is not clear whether this is a
good idea as it may hide bugs.

Currently the node, section and heading relations information is available
because all the corresponding Perl elements can be rebuilt preemptively.
It could be more relevant to have accessors instead such that the
Perl information can be built on demand.

indices API is missing in TreeElementConverter. Also maybe an API for output
units (for formats using output units).

No extra/info taken into account in new_element_from_sv.

accessors for TreeElements:
 * parent [OK]
 * type [OK]
 * command_name [OK]
 * source marks
    SourceMarksCount
    SourceMark(n)
 * attributes (extra/info)
     getAttribute (name) [OK]
     attributeCount ()
     getAttributeNo (no)
     maybe: moveToFirstAttribute ()
            moveToNextAttribute ()

 * associated_unit? <- output units API

Tree access
 ChildElementCount [OK]
 ChildElement(n) [OK]

Cross references:
 * getTargetById [OK, but untested]

